            <div class="faq-question">What is Obesity?</div>
            <div class="faq-answer">
                <p>Obesity is a medical condition characterized by excessive accumulation of body fat to the extent that it may have a negative impact on a person's health.Obesity is generally caused by a combination of genetic, environmental, and behavioral factors. Excessive calorie intake, sedentary lifestyle, lack of physical activity, unhealthy eating habits, hormonal imbalances, certain medications, and genetic predisposition can contribute to the development of obesity.</p>

            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
            <div class="faq-question">How to prevent/deal with Obesity?</div>
            <div class="faq-answer">
                <p>
                    Preventing obesity involves adopting a healthy lifestyle and making sustainable changes to promote weight management. Here are some key strategies to help prevent obesity:
                    <br />
                    <br />
                    1. Balanced and Nutritious Diet: Focus on consuming a balanced diet that includes a variety of fruits, vegetables, whole grains, lean proteins, and healthy fats. Limit the intake of processed foods, sugary drinks, and high-fat foods. Pay attention to portion sizes and practice mindful eating.
                    <br />
                    <br />
                    2. Regular Physical Activity: Engage in regular physical activity to burn calories and maintain a healthy weight. Aim for at least 150 minutes of moderate-intensity aerobic activity or 75 minutes of vigorous-intensity aerobic activity per week, along with strength training exercises for muscle strengthening.
                    <br />
                    <br />
                    3. Get Sufficient Sleep: Establish regular sleep patterns and aim for 7-9 hours of quality sleep each night. Inadequate sleep can disrupt hormones that regulate hunger and appetite, leading to weight gain.
                    <br />
                    <br />
                    4. Manage Stress: Find healthy ways to manage stress, as it can contribute to emotional eating and unhealthy food choices. Engage in activities like exercise, meditation, yoga, or hobbies to reduce stress levels.
                    <br />
                    <br />
                    5. Monitor Weight Regularly: Keep track of your weight and body measurements periodically to identify any changes or trends. Regular monitoring can help you take timely action and make necessary adjustments to your lifestyle..
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>
